    body: "Standard advance directive forms work fine for most heterosexual married couples because the law assumes a spouse will make decisions consistent with the patient's wishes. For LGBTQ+ seniors, especially those with hostile or estranged biological family, the standard forms need some additions. The good news is that the additions are short, do not require a lawyer, and dramatically increase the legal weight of your wishes when conflicts arise.\n\nThe core documents are familiar: the healthcare proxy (covered in the previous guide), the living will, the durable power of attorney for finances, and the HIPAA authorization. Each one has standard fields, and each one has space for additional instructions. The additional language is where LGBTQ+ specific protection lives.\n\nThe living will is your statement of what kind of medical care you want at the end of life: feeding tubes, ventilators, resuscitation, comfort-only care, organ donation, and so on. The standard form addresses these clinical questions but does not usually mention chosen family, religious or funeral preferences, or how you want your gender identity respected if you cannot speak for yourself. Adding two or three sentences covering these issues makes a real difference. For transgender seniors especially, a clear statement that you want your chosen name, pronouns, and gender identity respected in death (including in obituaries, funeral arrangements, and on the death certificate when possible) prevents a hostile family from undoing your transition after you are gone.\n\nThe durable power of attorney for finances is separate from the healthcare proxy and at least as important. It names someone (usually your partner) to handle your money, pay your bills, manage your investments, and sign legal documents on your behalf if you cannot. Without it, if you suffer a stroke or develop dementia, your partner has no legal authority to access joint accounts, pay your medical bills, or sell assets to fund your care. Even with joint accounts, banks routinely freeze accounts on a major medical event until a power of attorney is presented. The form is free, available from every state bar association or AARP, and takes about an hour to complete.\n\nThe HIPAA authorization deserves a second look because hospitals and nursing homes increasingly use it to control who hears about your care, not just to share your medical record. A well-written HIPAA authorization lists your partner, your designated chosen family, and clearly states that providers may communicate with these people about all aspects of your care, including treatment decisions, prognosis, and end-of-life planning.\n\nFinally, none of these documents work if they cannot be found. A 2024 study from the National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization found that 27 percent of advance directives are not in the medical record at the moment they are needed. Use the storage and distribution checklist in this guide so your documents follow you wherever you go.\n\n(Sources: AARP Free State-Specific Power of Attorney Forms; NHPCO 2024 advance directive study; Lambda Legal Take the Power LGBTQ+ Legal Toolkit; SAGE 2024 LGBT Older Adult Legal Resources; HHS Office for Civil Rights HIPAA Privacy Rule guidance, accessed May 2026)",
