    body: "Several national organizations exist primarily to support LGBTQ+ older adults. Their services are free, their staff are trained, and their reach is national. Knowing which organization to call for which problem saves hours of frustration. This guide covers the seven most useful resources, what each one does, when to call, and what to expect.\n\nThe SAGE LGBTQ+ Elder Hotline (1-877-360-LGBT or 1-877-360-5428) is the front door for almost any LGBTQ+ aging issue. Run by SAGE since 2014, the hotline is staffed by trained peer counselors. They handle calls about isolation, discrimination at a care facility, finding LGBTQ-friendly providers, mental health support, partner caregiving, and general questions about LGBTQ+ aging. Available 4 p.m. to midnight Eastern, seven days a week. Calls are confidential. The hotline serves LGBTQ+ seniors, their chosen family, professional caregivers, and allies. If you do not know who to call, start here.\n\nThe GLMA Provider Directory (glma.org/find_a_provider) is the largest national directory of LGBTQ-friendly healthcare providers. GLMA (formerly the Gay and Lesbian Medical Association) is the professional association of LGBTQ+ healthcare providers. The directory is free, searchable by ZIP code and specialty, and includes primary care doctors, mental health providers, dentists, specialists, and increasingly senior care providers. Each listing notes any specialties relevant to LGBTQ+ patients (HIV care, transgender medicine, lesbian women's health, etc.). Use it to find a primary care doctor when you move, when your current doctor retires, or when you need a specialist who will not require you to explain the basics.\n\nLambda Legal's Help Desk (1-866-542-8336) handles legal questions specific to LGBTQ+ Americans. The Help Desk does not provide direct legal representation in most cases, but it provides legal information, refers you to lawyers in your state who handle LGBTQ+ cases, and tracks discrimination patterns nationally. The Help Desk has handled thousands of elder cases over the years: discrimination at nursing homes, healthcare proxy disputes, transgender ID and benefits issues, employment discrimination affecting older workers, and estate planning challenges. Available Monday through Friday during business hours in each U.S. time zone.\n\nThe other four resources are equally important but more specialized. The National Resource Center on LGBTQ+ Aging (lgbtagingcenter.org) is the federal information hub. AARP's Pride section (aarp.org/pride) publishes plain-language guides on LGBTQ+ retirement and caregiving. The Trevor Project (1-866-488-7386) handles LGBTQ+ crisis intervention for all ages including seniors with suicidal thoughts. The Trans Lifeline (1-877-565-8860) provides peer support specifically for transgender people and is staffed entirely by trans people.\n\nSave these numbers in your phone now, before you need them. Print this list and tape it inside a kitchen cabinet or attach it to your refrigerator. Many LGBTQ+ seniors live alone, and the first call after a crisis matters.\n\n(Sources: SAGE LGBTQ+ Elder Hotline program page; GLMA Provider Directory; Lambda Legal Help Desk webpage; National Resource Center on LGBTQ+ Aging; AARP Pride section, accessed May 2026)",
